NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at| Because you thoughtfully stripped the hand, East has to give you a trick. He either will lead a club, and when I play last with the @CAKJ, I’ll never lose a trick in that suit. |
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|If he leads back a red card, where you’re void in both hands, you will slough a club from one hand and ruff in the other, and now you don’t lose any club tricks.|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|So here’s a hand – and this is a familiar theme in bridge – that yes, you do need to know the right way to play a suit in a vacuum, but on some hands, the proper technique in a suit is not the right way to play a hand – that’s why you always have to think about other suits, and not just focus on one.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT|^B@2
^B@2^*BMM: ^*NI knew it all along. I spent so many years to learn how to play a suit in a ^*Ivacuum^*N and now he tells me, "But not on all hands." But what if I am in the vacuum all the time? Please don't send me your answer. I already know it -:). Please click the forward arrow to see Howard's explanation of why on this hand it is wrong to cover the @SQ with the @SK.|
